Description
Who doesn't love cookies? Try to figure out the best one.

Target URL:
http://wily-courier.picoctf.net:65086/

🎯 Objective
The goal of this challenge is to understand how the website uses HTTP cookies and manipulate them to discover the flag.

🔎 Step 1 — Exploring the Website
*When opening the challenge website, a page appeared asking the user to select a cookie type.
*Each time a cookie was selected, the website responded with a message such as:
*That is a tasty cookie!

*Since the challenge is categorized under Web Exploitation, it suggested that the vulnerability might involve client-side data manipulation.

🔍 Step 2 — Inspecting Cookies in the Browser
To analyze how the website works, I opened Developer Tools in the browser.
Right Click → Inspect → Application → Cookies

Inside the cookie storage, I found a cookie named:
name

Initially, the value looked like:
name = -1

After selecting different cookies on the webpage, the value changed to numbers like:
name = 0
name = 1
name = 2
name = 3

This showed that the website was using the cookie value to identify which cookie was selected.

🧠 Step 3 — Testing Different Cookie Values
Since the cookie value was simply a number, I suspected that the server might have a list of cookies indexed by numbers.
Therefore, I manually modified the cookie value in Developer Tools.

Steps:
Open Developer Tools
Go to Application → Cookies
Find the cookie named name
Change the value to different numbers
Refresh the page

I tried several values such as:
name = 10
name = 15
name = 18
name = 20

Each time I refreshed the page, the response changed.

🏁 Step 4 — Finding the Flag
After testing several cookie values, one of the values caused the website to display the flag.

The flag appeared directly in the webpage response.
